    rationale: "Aminoglycosides (gentamicin, tobramycin, amikacin) are taken up by cochlear outer hair cells via mechanosensory channels. Inside the cell, they generate reactive oxygen species (free radicals) that cause oxidative damage to mitochondria and cell membranes, leading to irreversible hair cell death. The basal turn (high-frequency region) is affected first. This damage is permanent because cochlear hair cells do not regenerate in mammals. Sodium channel blockade, prostaglandin inhibition, and NMDA receptor antagonism are not the primary mechanisms of aminoglycoside ototoxicity.",
