    rationale: "The optic chiasm is where nasal retinal fibers from each eye cross to the contralateral optic tract. A lesion at the chiasm (classically a pituitary adenoma compressing from below) interrupts these crossing fibers, eliminating the temporal visual fields of both eyes \u2014 producing bitemporal hemianopsia. Homonymous hemianopsia results from post-chiasmal lesions. A monocular central scotoma suggests optic nerve or macular pathology. A quadrantanopsia suggests a partial optic radiation lesion.",
