    rationale: "Compression of the lacrimal sac (located at the medial canthus) is the regurgitation test for nasolacrimal duct obstruction. When the duct is obstructed, secretions and bacteria accumulate in the lacrimal sac. Pressure on the sac forces this mucopurulent material back through the canaliculi and out the punctum \u2014 confirming obstruction (dacryocystitis or nasolacrimal duct stenosis). Conjunctivitis does not produce regurgitation from the punctum on compression. Meibomian glands open along the lid margin, not the punctum. Dacryoadenitis involves the lacrimal gland (superolateral orbit), not the lacrimal sac.",
