    rationale: "A pearly white mass behind the TM with conductive hearing loss in the context of recurrent otitis media and Eustachian tube dysfunction is the classic description of a cholesteatoma. It is composed of accumulated keratin from a TM retraction pocket and is locally destructive. Tympanosclerosis appears as white calcified plaques on the TM itself, not as a mass behind it. Glomus tympanicum is a vascular tumor appearing as a red pulsatile mass. Otosclerosis causes conductive hearing loss from stapes fixation but has no visible mass on otoscopy.",
